To write a date in Japanese, you can format the numbers with each time period suffix. Dates in Japan are written year-month-day, either with Kanji or with - characters. More often than not, these are writen with western (arabic) numerals.
--
front: 2014年4月12日
back: にせんじゅうよんねん・よんがつ・じゅうににち, April 12, 2014
--
Calendar years are written using the year number with the [年]{ねん} suffix.
--
front: 2015年
back: にせんじゅうごねん, 2015
--
Another kind of year used in Japan is the era-based system, called [年号]{ねんごう} in Japanese. This is often used in ceremonies and when referring to one's year of birth. The era name changes for each new Emperor of Japan. The first year of each era is called [元年]{がんねん}. After that, each year is written as the era name followed by the year into the era, and the suffix [年]{ねん}.
--
front: 諸和二年
back: しょわにねん, 2nd year of Showa era (1927)
--
front: 平成元年
back: へいせいがんねん, 1st year of Heisei era (1988)
--
front: 平成二十七年
back: へいせい・にじゅうなな・ねん, 27th year of Heisei era (2015)
--
